  <static seed="64" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions20.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{2}{5} + \frac{2}{7}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{24}{35}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>5</m> and <m>7</m> is <m>35</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{2}{5}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>35</m>, we multiply <m>7</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{2}{5} \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 7}{5 \cdot 7}\\ \amp = \frac{14}{35}\end{aligned} }</m></p>
<p>Similarly, we change the second fraction<rsq/>s denominator to <m>35</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{2}{7} \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 5}{7 \cdot 5}\\ \amp = \frac{10}{35} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can add those two fractions. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{2}{5} + \frac{2}{7}
        \amp = \frac{14}{35} + \frac{10}{35} \\
        \amp = \frac{14 + 10}{35} \\
        \amp = \frac{24}{35}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{24}{35}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
